{
  "style": "IEEE",
  "texts": [
    "Commonly, a linearization-based approximation of the stochastic dynamics in terms of its mean µ x k and covariance Σ k is employed, which leads to the following approximate reformulation of the GP-MPC optimization problem [3]:min u0,...,u N -1 µ x 0,...,µ x N, Σ x 0,...,Σ x N N -1 k=0 l(µ x k, u k) + M (µ x N) (14a) s.t.",
    "µ x 0 = x(t),(14b)Σ x 0 = 0,(14c)µ x k+1 = f (µ x k, u k) + B d g(µ x k, u k),(14d)Σ x k+1 = Ψ k (µ x k, u k, Σ x k),(14e)0 ≥ h(µ x k, u k) + β(µ x k, u k, Σ x k), (14f) 0 ≥ h N (µ x N) + β N (µ x N, Σ x N).",
    "(14g)Thereby, the discrete-time covariance dynamics are given asΨ k (µ x k, u k, Σ x k) = A k Σ x k A ⊤ k + B d Σ g (µ x k, u k)B ⊤ d + Σ w,(15)whereA(µ x k, u k).",
    "= ∂ ∂x (f (x, u k) + B d g(x, u k)) x=µ x kdenotes the Jacobian of the nominal and GP mean dynamics with respect to the (mean) state.",
    "Component-wise for each j = 1,..., n h, the nominal constraints h j are tightened byβ j (µ x k, u k, Σ k)."
  ],
